Data Frames

In this exercise well investigate a data set from (http://www.gapminder.org), a site that contains a wealth of data and visualizations related to health, wealth, population, etc. of countries of the world. Typical datasets from (http://www.gapminder.org) are somewhat messy, with a lot of missing observations, so today well work with data extracted from the more complete data sets by Jenny Bryan at UBC. First we load the data into R.

location <- "http://blue.for.msu.edu/FOR875/data/gapminder.tsv"
gapminder <- read.delim(location)

The str function reports on the structure of an object in R. Its often useful to use str when working with a new dataset.

str(gapminder)

The output from str shows the gapminder data frame has six variables, including country (a factor), year (an integer), pop (numeric), continent (a factor), lifeExp (numeric), and gdpPercap (numeric).

Floating point arithmetic

R, as does most software, uses floating point arithmetic, which is not the same as the arithmetic we learn, because computers cannot represent all numbers exactly. This has important consequences when we test for equality of numbers and in other settings well explore in the course.

Here are a few examples.

First, would you expect 0.2 == 0.6/3 to return TRUE or FALSE? Test it out.

# TODO 4.9: Enter 0.2 == 0.6/3 and see what happens. Explain the potentially surprising result in commented text.
0.2 == 0.6/3
[1] FALSE
# Because 0.2 is a floating point that could be the binary approximation of the true decimal value. We don't know the numbers beyond the precise range given by R as 24-bit. Thus x1 == x2 is FALSE in most case even though the answer numberically looks same.

Next consider the vector point3 created below.

point3 <- c(0.3, 0.4 - 0.1, 0.5 - 0.2, 0.6 - 0.3, 0.7 - 0.4)
point3
[1] 0.3 0.3 0.3 0.3 0.3

Test whether each element of point3 is equal to 0.3

# TODO 4.10: Perform the test here
0.3 == 0.3   
[1] TRUE
0.4 - 0.1 == 0.3    
[1] FALSE
0.5 - 0.2 == 0.3   
[1] TRUE
0.6 - 0.3 == 0.3   
[1] TRUE
0.7 - 0.4 == 0.3   
[1] FALSE

.Machine is a list that holds information on the numerical characteristics of the machine R is running on, such as the largest double or integer and the machines precision. For example

.Machine$double.eps
[1] 2.220446e-16

is the smallest positive floating-point number x such that 1 + x != 1. The false in point3 == 0.3 and 0.2 == 0.6/3 show us that using floating point arithmetic with logical operators can yield unexpected results. The false for 0.2 == 0.6/3 is because floating point arithmetic of 0.6/3 will equal 0.2 + x, where x is some very small value.

If you want to safely apply a logical tests to computed values, R provides a set of functions that test with a given tolerance, e.g., equal up to 1.5e-8 digits. For example,

all.equal(0.2, 0.6/3)
[1] TRUE

We revisit this topic in Chapter 7.3 in the course text.

Heres another example of the limitations of floating point arithmetic. In calculus we were taught the base of the natural logarithm is \[ e = \lim_{n\to\infty} (1 + 1/n)^n \] So in principle we should be able to get closer and closer approximations to \(e\) by using larger and larger values of \(n\) in the above expression (\(e\) is something close to 2.718282). See here if you need a refresher.

Lets try a few.

n <- 100
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 2.704814
n <- 10000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 2.718146
n <- 1000000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 2.71828
n <- 100000000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 2.718282

So far things are looking good. Investigate what happens as you increase \(n\). Each time multiply \(n\) by 10. Continue until you get to 10000000000000000. What happens?

n <- 1000000000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 2.718282
n <- 10000000000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 2.718282
n <- 100000000000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 2.718282

Things are started going weird beyond this point on my machine (i.e., the approximation is no longer close to \(e\) = 2.71828). The majority computers should start to give bad answers around this size of \(n\).

n <- 1000000000000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 2.718523
n <- 10000000000000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 2.71611
n <- 100000000000000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 2.71611
n <- 1000000000000000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 3.035035
n <- 10000000000000000
(1 + 1/n)^n
[1] 1

You dont have to understand exactly how your machine handles floating point numbers, but it is good to be aware that testing for equality of numbers may result in unexpected behavior.
